      <hedline>
        <hl1>In the Mideast, a Bridge Too Far; Enlist Carter's Help</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Richard H Escobales Jr letter, commenting on Jimmy Carter's August 6 Op-Ed article, says his perceptive remarks are reasons why his services should be sought when Middle East peace talks continue</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The perceptive remarks of Jimmy Carter provide one more reason why his services should be sought when Middle East peace talks continue (''A Jerusalem Settlement Everyone Can Live With,'' Op-Ed, Aug. 6).</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The perceptive remarks of Jimmy Carter provide one more reason why his services should be sought when Middle East peace talks continue (''A Jerusalem Settlement Everyone Can Live With,'' Op-Ed, Aug. 6).</p>
        <p>Indeed, one can ask why the services of the former president, who was instrumental in establishing peace between Egypt and Israel, weren't enlisted in this latest round of the peace process.</p>
        <p>RICHARD H. ESCOBALES JR.  Buffalo, Aug. 7, 2000</p>
      </block>
